    <note>Sun(1) Changqing [1514] He used the yin of his maternal grandfather, Zhu(1) Sun [521], to enter the civil service. He lacked literary ability, but was strong in administrative matters (zhengshi). The funerary inscription for his wife does not include the mingzi for her patrilineal ancestors, but includes their titles, which identified Wang(2) Li [21274] as her father, whose funerary inscription lists Sun(1) Changqing as a son-in-law. Zhang(1) Hui(4)'s [7157] father-in-law. XCB, 188.7a; Wang Anshi, WJ, 100.1028-29 (wife, born Wang, who died in 1059 at age 53); Lu Dian, WJ, 15.19b-20a (identical to inscription for wife drafted by Wang(2) Anshi [1762] and Lu(5) Dian [8098] received the jinshi 11 years after her death; i.e., in some way Wang Anshi's draft inscription found its way into Lu Dian's collected papers); Shen Gou, WJ, 2.12b; SS, 331.1a-2a. Weiyang Z (1542), 22.34a-35b. CBD, 3, 1922.</note>
